'''Kukur√°''' (Cucur√°, Kokura) is a [[spurious language]], fabricated by an interpreter in Brazil.
When [[Alberto Vojtƒõch Friƒç]] visited Rio Verde, Brazil, in 1901 he took with him a [[Pai Tavytera people|Kaingu√°]] Indian called Guzm√°n who said he spoke the language of the local ''[[Chavante]]'' people. A word list was published for the so-called Kukur√° language, thought to be an isolate, in 1931. In 1932 [[Curt Nimuendaj√∫]], who had visited the Rio Verde in 1909 and 1913, showed that Guzm√°n's wordlist consisted half of fake words and half of mispronounced [[Guarani language|Guaran√≠]]. There was no resemblance to the [[Ofay√© language]] that was actually spoken in the region.<ref>{{cite book|last1=Campbell|first1=Lyle|last2=Grondona|first2=Ver√≥nica|title=The Indigenous Languages of South America: A Comprehensive Guide|url=https://books.google.com/books?id=pA-ryJRcG3AC&pg=PA133|accessdate=2013-04-24|date=2012-01-27|publisher=Walter de Gruyter|isbn=978-3-11-025803-5|page=133}}</ref>
